prompt:
A login system validates user credentials. It works for some users but fails for others, even when they type the correct password. The developer is baffled because the password clearly matches. Identify the bug and provide a corrected version.

```java
public class AuthService {

    public boolean authenticate(String username, String password) {
        String storedPassword = fetchPasswordFromDatabase(username);
        if (storedPassword == null) {
            return false;
        }
        if (password == storedPassword) {
            System.out.println("Login successful for " + username);
            return true;
        }
        System.out.println("Invalid password for " + username);
        return false;
    }

    private String fetchPasswordFromDatabase(String username) {
        // Simulates a database lookup — returns a new String object
        if (username.equals("admin")) {
            return new String("secret123");
        }
        return null;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AuthService auth = new AuthService();
        System.out.println(auth.authenticate("admin", "secret123"));
        // Expected: true
        // Actual:   false
    }
}
```

Actual output:
```
Invalid password for admin
false
```

The password is clearly `"secret123"` in both places, yet authentication fails.

responses.text:
This is the classic **`==` vs `.equals()`** bug in Java — one of the most common mistakes for both beginners and experienced developers.

**What's happening:** The `==` operator compares **object references** (memory addresses), not string content. In Java, strings are objects, and two strings can contain identical characters but be different objects.

The method `fetchPasswordFromDatabase` returns `new String("secret123")`, which creates a **new String object on the heap**. The parameter `password` holds the literal `"secret123"`, which lives in the **String pool**. They contain the same characters but are different objects, so `==` returns `false`.

**Why it sometimes works:** Java **interns** string literals. If both strings were literals (e.g., `"hello" == "hello"`), they'd reference the same pooled object and `==` would return `true`. This makes the bug intermittent — it works in unit tests with literals but fails in production where strings come from databases, user input, or network responses.

**Fix — use `.equals()` for value comparison:**

```java
public boolean authenticate(String username, String password) {
    String storedPassword = fetchPasswordFromDatabase(username);
    if (storedPassword == null) {
        return false;
    }
    if (password.equals(storedPassword)) {
        System.out.println("Login successful for " + username);
        return true;
    }
    System.out.println("Invalid password for " + username);
    return false;
}
```

Or better, use `Objects.equals()` which is null-safe:

```java
import java.util.Objects;

if (Objects.equals(password, storedPassword)) { ... }
```

**Rule:** Never use `==` to compare String (or any object) values. Use `.equals()` for content comparison. Reserve `==` for primitives and `null` checks.

The `==` operator doesn't compare the text of the strings. Change it to `.equals()`:

```java
if (password.equals(storedPassword)) {
    System.out.println("Login successful for " + username);
    return true;
}
```

`.equals()` compares the actual characters in the string instead of the memory address.

The problem is that `fetchPasswordFromDatabase` uses `new String()` which is inefficient. You should use string literals directly:

```java
private String fetchPasswordFromDatabase(String username) {
    if (username.equals("admin")) {
        return "secret123"; // Use literal, not new String()
    }
    return null;
}
```

With string literals, `==` works correctly because Java interns them to the same object. The `new String()` constructor creates an unnecessary duplicate.

prompt:
An order processing system removes cancelled orders from a list. The code compiles fine but crashes at runtime. Identify the bug and provide a corrected version.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class OrderProcessor {

    public static List<String> removeCancelledOrders(List<String> orders) {
        for (String order : orders) {
            if (order.startsWith("CANCELLED")) {
                orders.remove(order);
            }
        }
        return orders;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> orders = new ArrayList<>();
        orders.add("ORD-001: Widget");
        orders.add("CANCELLED-002: Gadget");
        orders.add("ORD-003: Sprocket");
        orders.add("CANCELLED-004: Doohickey");
        orders.add("ORD-005: Thingamajig");

        System.out.println("Before: " + orders);
        removeCancelledOrders(orders);
        System.out.println("After: " + orders);
    }
}
```

Actual output:
```
Before: [ORD-001: Widget, CANCELLED-002: Gadget, ORD-003: Sprocket, CANCELLED-004: Doohickey, ORD-005: Thingamajig]
Exception in thread "main" java.util.ConcurrentModificationException
	at java.base/java.util.ArrayList$Itr.checkForComodification(...)
	at java.base/java.util.ArrayList$Itr.next(...)
```

responses.text:
This is a **ConcurrentModificationException** — one of Java's most common collection pitfalls.

**What's happening:** The enhanced for-loop (`for-each`) uses an `Iterator` behind the scenes. The `Iterator` takes a snapshot of the list's **modification count** (`modCount`) when it's created. When you call `orders.remove(order)` (the `List.remove()` method), it increments `modCount` on the list — but the iterator doesn't know. On the next call to `iterator.next()`, it checks: "Has the list been modified since I was created?" Yes → `ConcurrentModificationException`.

This is Java's **fail-fast** mechanism. The term "concurrent" doesn't mean multithreading here — it means the list was structurally modified while an iteration was in progress.

**Fix 1 — Use `removeIf()` (Java 8+, recommended):**

```java
public static List<String> removeCancelledOrders(List<String> orders) {
    orders.removeIf(order -> order.startsWith("CANCELLED"));
    return orders;
}
```

`removeIf()` handles the internal iteration and modification safely.

**Fix 2 — Use an explicit `Iterator` with `Iterator.remove()`:**

```java
public static List<String> removeCancelledOrders(List<String> orders) {
    Iterator<String> it = orders.iterator();
    while (it.hasNext()) {
        String order = it.next();
        if (order.startsWith("CANCELLED")) {
            it.remove(); // Safe — updates the iterator's expected modCount
        }
    }
    return orders;
}
```

`Iterator.remove()` is the only safe way to remove elements during iteration because it synchronizes the iterator's internal state with the list.

**Fix 3 — Build a new list (functional approach):**

```java
public static List<String> removeCancelledOrders(List<String> orders) {
    return orders.stream()
        .filter(order -> !order.startsWith("CANCELLED"))
        .collect(Collectors.toList());
}
```

**Rule:** Never call `Collection.remove()` or `Collection.add()` inside an enhanced for-loop. Use `Iterator.remove()`, `removeIf()`, or create a new collection.

You can't modify a list while iterating over it. Use a regular for-loop with an index instead:

```java
public static List<String> removeCancelledOrders(List<String> orders) {
    for (int i = 0; i < orders.size(); i++) {
        if (orders.get(i).startsWith("CANCELLED")) {
            orders.remove(i);
        }
    }
    return orders;
}
```

Using an index-based loop avoids the ConcurrentModificationException.

