An HR system stores employees in a `HashSet` to prevent duplicates. Two employees with the same ID are being added as separate entries. The developer overrode `equals()` but the set doesn't detect duplicates. Identify the bug and provide a corrected version.

```java
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class Employee {
    private int id;
    private String name;

    public Employee(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (this == obj) return true;
        if (obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
        Employee other = (Employee) obj;
        return this.id == other.id;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Employee{id=" + id + ", name='" + name + "'}";
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<Employee> employees = new HashSet<>();
        employees.add(new Employee(101, "Alice"));
        employees.add(new Employee(101, "Alice Johnson"));
        employees.add(new Employee(102, "Bob"));

        System.out.println("Set size: " + employees.size());
        System.out.println("Expected: 2 (id 101 is duplicate)");
        System.out.println("Employees: " + employees);
    }
}
```

Actual output:
```
Set size: 3
Expected: 2 (id 101 is duplicate)
Employees: [Employee{id=102, name='Bob'}, Employee{id=101, name='Alice'}, Employee{id=101, name='Alice Johnson'}]
```

Both employees with id 101 are in the set despite `equals()` returning `true` for them.

responses.text:
This is the **equals/hashCode contract violation** — one of Java's most important rules that LLMs frequently get wrong.

**The contract:** If `a.equals(b)` returns `true`, then `a.hashCode()` must equal `b.hashCode()`. You overrode `equals()` but inherited the default `hashCode()` from `Object`, which returns a value based on the object's **memory address**. Since `new Employee(101, "Alice")` and `new Employee(101, "Alice Johnson")` are different objects, they have different default hash codes.

**How HashSet works internally:**
1. Compute `hashCode()` of the new element
2. Use that hash to determine which **bucket** to place it in
3. Only if another element is in the **same bucket** does it call `equals()` to check for duplicates

Your two Employee(101) objects get different hash codes → different buckets → `equals()` is never called → both are added.

**Fix — override `hashCode()` using the same fields as `equals()`:**

```java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Integer.hashCode(id);
}
```

Or using `Objects.hash()` for multi-field hashing:

```java
import java.util.Objects;

@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(id);
}
```

Now both Employee(101, ...) objects produce the same hash code → same bucket → `equals()` detects the duplicate → only one is kept.

**Rule:** Always override `hashCode()` when you override `equals()`. Use the **same fields** in both methods. This contract is critical for HashMap, HashSet, Hashtable, and any hash-based collection.

**IDE support:** IntelliJ and Eclipse can auto-generate both methods together — use this to avoid mistakes.

HashSet uses `hashCode()` to find elements. You need to add a `hashCode()` method:

```java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(id);
}
```

Without `hashCode()`, the set treats objects at different memory addresses as different entries.

The issue is that `HashSet` doesn't use `equals()` for comparison. Try using a `TreeSet` instead, which uses `compareTo()`:

```java
import java.util.TreeSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    // ... existing fields and constructor ...

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Employee other) {
        return Integer.compare(this.id, other.id);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<Employee> employees = new TreeSet<>();
        employees.add(new Employee(101, "Alice"));
        employees.add(new Employee(101, "Alice Johnson"));
        employees.add(new Employee(102, "Bob"));
        System.out.println("Set size: " + employees.size());
    }
}
```

TreeSet maintains sorted order and properly detects duplicates through comparison.

